            <ArticleTitle>A quality management intervention to improve clinical laboratory use in acute myocardial infarction.</ArticleTitle>
            <Pagination>
                <MedlinePgn>11-4</MedlinePgn>
            </Pagination>
            <Abstract>
                <AbstractText Label="OBJECTIVE" NlmCategory="OBJECTIVE">To assess the effect of a total quality management (TQM) approach on the appropriateness of clinical laboratory testing of patients with acute myocardial infarction.</AbstractText>
                <AbstractText Label="DESIGN" NlmCategory="METHODS">Retrospective, control-group, quasi-experimental study.</AbstractText>
                <AbstractText Label="SETTING" NlmCategory="METHODS">Two metropolitan teaching hospitals: one involved in the intervention (TQM experimental group); the other had no intervention (control group).</AbstractText>
                <AbstractText Label="INTERVENTION" NlmCategory="METHODS">A multidisciplinary team involved in the development of improvement strategies, including laboratory testing guidelines, education programs, data collection, monitoring and feedback.</AbstractText>
                <AbstractText Label="OUTCOME MEASURES" NlmCategory="METHODS">Total number of requested clinically indicated and non-clinically indicated tests.</AbstractText>
                <AbstractText Label="RESULTS" NlmCategory="RESULTS">The proportion of clinically indicated tests that were requested increased from 77.5% to 88.2% (P &lt; 0.01) and the number of non-clinically indicated tests was reduced by 81.7% with the introduction of the TQM strategies (P &lt; 0.01).</AbstractText>
                <AbstractText Label="CONCLUSIONS" NlmCategory="CONCLUSIONS">The introduction of a TQM approach has improved the appropriateness of test ordering in acute myocardial infarction. The reduction in non-clinically indicated tests could produce substantial savings in hospital pathology costs, and the increase in clinically indicated tests provides better patient care.</AbstractText>
            </Abstract>
